reviews.review_text: Swet Awsome set love the high timeand where is the us blues encore????
No stronger than dirt! There is No stronger than dirt! It just isn't there. It is just a jam, but it is not that tune!

Amazing matrix! This matrix is absolutely perfect! No delay or fade between the two tapes, and full rich sound! This is one of the best matrix recordings on the archive for sure, and what a great show too! I love '76 because it's a year I don't get to often, but when I do it's always a mind-bender! I love the Playin' here, maybe even more than versions I have heard from '77! They aren't just doodling away on chords, they are creating! This matrix captures the pure sounds of each individual instrument as you would hear it in the audience! The Dead are in a tight groove this night, permeated by that lazy '76 flow. Every note is thought out and constructed. The Cosmic Charlie is simply fascinating! The drummers are tuned into each other and the vocal harmonies are perfect. Too bad we don't have the complete show!

I almost forgot to mention how truly beautiful Donna sounds on this evening. Even her Playin' scream is more tempered.   

And that is "Stronger Than Dirt" you are hearing after Playin', it is a version they played a lot in '75, not the typical version you expect to hear from the studio album.

Saw DSO perform this At the Boulder Theatre. It was a great show to see as it was an unpredictable set list with a lot of nuggets. 

I believe this is the only Stronger Than Dirt outside of the few 75' hiatus performances. 

Just a very jazzy and different approach to what they were doing historically at this point. 

Look to the last night of this run for a solid second set as well, slightly more historically predictable, but still a good listen through.
matrix is where its at killer/smoker of a second set with beautiful versions of cosmic charlie and high time. A++ sound.

Definitely Not Stronger Than Dirt Or, as the wonderful instrumental piece is referred to on post-Jerry setlists, King Solomon's Marbles.
Phil's bass line at the beginning of this part of the jam is suggestive of STD/KSM but that's about it. Otherwise, none of the chord changes of the song, nor the 7/4 rhythm.

Stronger than Dirt DEFINITELY NOT Stronger than Dirt - different key, different time signature, and none of the signature lines. At the very start Jerry plays a run that sounds Dirt-ish and Phil plays a punchy line that sounds like it could go there, but nothing materializes. Later Keith hints at some Slipknot-like stuff; it would be more appropriate to call this a Slipknot jam if you have to label it (it's in the key of A and has roughly the right tempo). I just hear it as a cool jam.

Stronger than Dirt If you listen to the album version of KSM/STDOMTT, there is a part at about 3:40 that is similar to what Phil begins playing at the beginning of the jam here. It is a different key, mode and time sig but clearly it is just a lick he starts playing and it takes a moment for the band to get going as he is trying to play a non 4/4 lick but it won't stick so he backs off somewhat. It is very borderline whether it could be called "Stronger Than Dirt" but that suite was written by Lesh and there's enough of a trace to allow it. Clearly they stopped playing that song after 8/13/75 but strands remained
